defaultAll 
default11
default organisations work with white working class children and young people, and most also work with significant numbers of black and minority ethnic benef
defaulticiaries too. The portfolio was split, with half responding that they did not feel white working class young people faced specific challenges that might hold back their educational achievement, and half responding that they did. 
defaultHowever, all were knowledge
defaultable about the challenges to academic achievement facing young people across economically disadvantaged groups. 
defaultOf those who perceived specific challenges, 
defaultmany commented that the home lives of their white beneficiaries seemed more chaotic, and that their
default parents were less likely to push them to attend, and achieve at
default, school, than their BME peers:
default“There is a split between ‘school culture’ and ‘family culture’ – 
defaultsome 
defaultboys don’t know how to cope with the switch between the two. What the school teaches is not 
defaultalways 
defaultreinforced at home. We actually have to provide the kids with an ‘attachmen
defaultt’ to the school, if
default parents don’t provide this.’ - 
