defaultHow to Engage Young People defaultThere were many 
defaultsimilarities
default amongst the successful methods o
defaultur charities use
default to engage disadvantaged children and young people, either in mainstream education, or in ‘second chance’ a
defaultctivities designed to move them into education, training, or employment. 
defaultPersistence was common to nearly all, but it is worth going into more detail here, as we feel the lessons are essential for those working with young people in schools, health services
default, and employment services. 
default“[The key is] quiet tenacity. We approach parents with a focus on their children’s ‘emotional wellbe
defaulting’ and not ‘mental health’. We
default expect a ‘does not attend’ rate of about four, with children and/or parents finally attending o
defaultn the fifth appointment. This is different from CAMHS which has a ‘no follow up’ policy if a young person doesn’t attend.  Our staff are well-supported to maintain their persistence and resilience.
default Staff need to be expert, nuanced, supportive, and not ‘cli
defaultnical’.
default”
default – 
defaultSenior Manager, charity providing counselling services in schoolsdefault“We use an arts-based programme, because you can’t ‘fail’ the arts”. Our intake have a history of educational failure and any success is a huge motivator. Our curriculum builds li
defaultteracy and numeracy by stealth, as well as confidence. Clients are called ‘students’, and when they graduate the course, this is celebrated with a ceremony attended by parents and local dignitaries. We’re also happy to spend money on cabs to get latecomers
default in in the morning – the cabbie
defaults
default we use are happy to hammer on the door to get them out of bed, because getting them into a rout
defaulti
defaultne is crucial. It’s a good use of money because nothing is a bigger waste of money than an empty seat on a course.”
default – 
defaultCEO of a defaultcharity working with young offendersdefault‘’We go to where young people are – and we make them an initial offer that’s engaging: ‘just come and play football’. We fit in with the people who are already making a difference in a community – we don’t compete with 
defaultthem. We assess the young people to make sure an intervention is right for them – we don’t want to set them up to fail, because 
defaultthat’s happened to them before.”
default – 
defaultCOO of a charity using street football as a hook to reengage NEETs in learning default“
defaultThe key is 
defaultto engage young people in a coaching relationship. Many organisations say they do coaching but all our staff are actually fully trained coaches. The adult to adult relationship between a coach and a young person is crucial – teachers simply aren’t able to
default 
defaulthave this kind of relationship
default with pupils. Our staff need to be char
defaultismatic, and good listeners – bu
defaultt not afraid to challenge apathy or hopelessness. We meet young people in Job Centres and try to get a phone number. Then we call them repeatedly and expec
defaultt lots of rejection – typically, it will take three or four chances to get them to e
defaultnrol.”
default – 
defaultHead of Coaching for a charity working with NEETsdefault“
defaultThe first few years at our Centres might just be about having fun, learning a few skills, and making new friends
default from outside the immediate neighbourhood. After a few years, maybe at 14, staff are trusted and can ask questions about how things are going at school. The White working class kids we see are not used to being asked these questions, or if they are, they’r
defaulte not responding positively. Our staff open their eyes to different responses and options. It may sound like slow progress, but we’ve got 20% of kids coming from workless hom
defaultes with very chaotic home lives”
default 
default– Senior Manager at a charity providing youth cendefaulttres in the North Westdefault“
defaultThe quality of our staff is key to successful engagement – selection is stringent and training ta
defaultkes three months. Staff build up a very personal relationship with young people and demonstrate a strong commitment to them. We say ‘if
default you join us at 7 we still want to be seeing you every week when you’re 14’. Where else can a child get this individual commitment
default?
default”
default – 
defaultManager at a charity offering homework defaultclubs and academic supportdefault“
defaultWe often hear that teachers treat the young people we 
