default default- COO of a charity using street football as a hook to reengage NEETs in learning defaultThe Importance of Data defaultA crucial part of what we work with our portfolio organisations to achieve is called ‘impact management’. That is to say, the practice of measuring key indicators 
defaultin real-time 
defaultduring your work, and using the results to influence your practice, and resourci
defaultng, on a daily, weekly, and annual basis. There is substantial evidence to show that not only does this drive improved performance at an organisation level but it also 
defaultimproves outcomes for individual beneficiaries. 
defaultWe asked our organisations to tell us h
defaultow they used impact management, and real-time monitoring, in their practice, and to ensure they were doing a good job for children and young people. The methods varied, but there were similarities. 
default“Attendance of a young person is logged every week, and t
defaulthey are phoned if they don’t attend.”
default 
default– 
defaultManager at a charity offering homework defaultclubs and academic supportdefault“Continuous monitoring – adult to adult reflection and review – is part of the coaching process/culture. We know how every young person is doing at ev
defaultery stage of their time with us” - 
default– 
defaultHead of Coaching for a charity working with NEETsdefault“
defaultStaff receive their clinic
defaultal supervision on the same 
defaultday they see their clients [children and young people]. 
defaultThis means they’re 
defaultreporting
default on a child’s progress the same
default day they see them, and making plans for next steps”
default default- defaultSenior Manager, charity providing counselling services in schoolsdefault“Real-time monitoring of staff performance is routine – if any of the teams are submitting sub- standard results, they have to submit an improvement plan which is independently audited, and a site visit is carried out” 
default– 
defaultCEO of a charity working with youngdefault offendersdefault“Our use of data is formative and summative
default. Students have routine 1:1s with a Progression Coordinator, and their performance on the course is monitored. They, and we, need to know if there are any areas where they might be likely to fail, so it
default can be addressed.” - 
defaultCOO of a charity using street football as a hook to reengage NEETs in learning defaultThere is evidence that impact-led use of data is key in improving educational attainment in schools, including those with disadvantaged intakes. Our organ
defaultisations – some of the best-performing in the UK – are using data to ensure they know whether the children and young people 
defaultthey work with 
defaultare improving and benefitting. They use this feedback to put in place remedial plans if they are not. 
defaultIt is crucial 
defaultfor all schools to identify and track the right data. From the day a child enters school, staff should be able to see whether they are making academic progress, and be empowered to act quickly if they are not. Good GCSE results for the majority in a school
default are not acceptable, if a rump of pupils are allowed to underachieve, disrupt lessons, or simply not attend. 
defaultAs one of our respondents said, children can ‘hide’ in large schools. They cannot if a school is committed to tracking the progress of every child
default, and focussing attention, and resource, on those who need it. Tackling a child’s problems – whether academic, or in his wider life -  at 12 is more effective on every level than waiting until they are 16, and months away from failing to secure a single go
defaultod GSCE. 
defaultConclusionsdefaultWe would be delighted to talk w
defaultith the Education Select Committee about this res
defaultponse, the eleven interviews 
defaultconducted and the ongoing work of Impetus – The Private Equity Foundation.  We welcome the committee’s desire to better understand the challenges faced by white working class boy
defaults in the UK
default education system
default.  We hope that hearing from an engaged philanthropic funder and the voices of many expert practitioners working in and outside of school
default,
default is a useful contribution to the committees understanding of how 
defaultcollaboratively 
defaultwe 
defaultcan 
defaultwo
defaultrk towards an education system where every pupil, regardless of background is supported to succeed and transition successfully into the adult world of work and 
defaultbecome an active and engaged member of society.
